  <slides>

    <!-- Slide 1 -->
    <slide id="1">
      <content>
        <text>Topic: Integration by Substitution</text>
        <text>Evaluate the indefinite integral:</text>
        <math>\int 7(x+1)^6\,dx</math>
        <question>
          <text>Which of the following is the correct result?</text>
          <answers>
            <answer index="1">I = (x+1)^7</answer>
            <answer index="2">I = (x+1)^5 + c</answer>
            <answer index="3">I = (x+1)^5</answer>
            <answer index="4">I = (x+1)^7 + c</answer>
          </answers>
          <correctAnswer>4</correctAnswer>
          <explanation>Let u = x+1, du = dx. Then the integral becomes 7*u^6 du = u^7 + c = (x+1)^7 + c.</explanation>
        </question>
      </content>
    </slide>

    <!-- Slide 2 -->
    <slide id="2">
      <content>
        <text>Topic: Integration by Substitution</text>
        <text>Evaluate the indefinite integral:</text>
        <math>\int \cos(3x)\,dx</math>
        <question>
          <text>Which of the following is the correct result?</text>
          <answers>
            <answer index="1">sin(3x) + c</answer>
            <answer index="2">(1/3)sin(3x) + c</answer>
            <answer index="3">-sin(3x) + c</answer>
            <answer index="4">3sin(3x) + c</answer>
          </answers>
          <correctAnswer>2</correctAnswer>
          <explanation>Let u = 3x, du = 3dx, so dx = du/3. The integral becomes (1/3)*cos(u) du = (1/3)sin(u) + c = (1/3)sin(3x) + c.</explanation>
        </question>
      </content>
    </slide>

  </slides>
</learningContent>
